{{distinguish|Gobuntu|gOS (operating system)|Google Chrome OS}} '''Goobuntu''' is the unofficial name of a [[Linux distribution]], based on the 'long term support'-versions of [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]], that is used internally by [[Google]]. It adds a number of packages for in-house use, but does not have any other stark differences. Some have suggested that Google might plan to market the distribution more widely.<ref>[[The Register]] reports: [http://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/31/google_goes_desktop_linux/ Google at work on Linux]</ref><ref>[[Slashdot]] reports: [http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=06/11/22/1415221 "GoogleOS Scenarios"]</ref><ref>[[Slashdot]] reports: [http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=06/01/31/1519224 "Google Working on Desktop Linux"]</ref> While both Google and [[Mark Shuttleworth]], creator of Ubuntu, have confirmed that Goobuntu exists and is used internally,<ref>[[Mark Shuttleworth|Shuttleworth]]'s Blog post: [http://www.markshuttleworth.com/archives/20 Absolutely no truth to the rumour]</ref> both have strongly denied suggestions that Google has any plans to market the [[operating system]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Ars Technica]]|url=http://arstechnica.com/old/content/2006/01/6087.ars|title=Google denies plans to distribute OS based on Ubuntu|date=31 January 2006|first=Anders|last=Bylund}}</ref> Almost half of the 20,000 employees of Google use Goobuntu.<ref name="NYT10Jan09"> {{cite news|url = http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/11/business/11ubuntu.html?_r=2&th&emc=th|title = A Software Populist Who Doesnât Do Windows |accessdate = 2009-02-22|last = Vance|first = Ashlee|authorlink = |year = 2009|month = January | work=The New York Times}}</ref>
[[Mark Shuttleworth]] has confirmed that Google contributes [[patch (software)|patch]]es to Ubuntu.<ref>[[Mark Shuttleworth|Shuttleworth]]'s Blog post: [http://www.markshuttleworth.com/archives/20 Absolutely no truth to the rumour]</ref> Google has supported Ubuntu on several occasions, including hosting the Ubuntu Developer Summit. Nevertheless, Shuttleworth and Google representatives have denied any plans to release Goobuntu outside the company.
